Advanced regionalization in spatial statistics encompasses a range of modern, statistically rigorous methods—often using spatial regression, Bayesian clustering, decision trees, and spatial autocorrelation measures—to partition spatial data into meaningful regions, accounting for spatial dependence, heterogeneity, and uncertainty. These methods support improved modeling, inference, and prediction in spatially structured data.
